The first reports of grave robbing in Beiliu emerged in June, when a local man contacted police to say his grandfather's tomb had been broken into and the body removed, according to Xinhua.

In China the deceased are often buried in large tombs which allow people to perform ancestor worship rituals. Veneration of the dead by living relatives in deeply rooted in Chinese culture.

In July a grave robber surnamed Zhong was arrested and confessed to stealing the body.

He added that he had also taken more than 20 other corpses from graveyards in surrounding villages, putting them into bags and transporting them into neighbouring Guangdong province.

There, he claims, two funeral management officials surnamed He and Dong purchased the bodies.

According to local media the men later told investigating officers that they had burned the corpses in order to hit a controversial monthly cremation quota.

