Mr Dong is said to have paid approximately £300 each for 10 corpses, while Mr He paid roughly £150 per body. It is not yet known how many the latter ended up purchasing.

Xinhua reported the deals were allegedly 'approved' by the government, adding that since the arrests a number of other villages have come forward to report bodies missing from graves.

The monthly cremation quota has caused controversy because ancestor worship is deeply rooted in Chinese culture. Many Chinese people also believe a person's body must be left untouched in order for them to enter the afterlife without difficulty.

The regulations have led to a number of families secretly burying family members to get around the law, and there were even reports of elderly people committing suicide before the quota came into place so they could be guaranteed a traditional burial.

